Heuristics¶

Using rough guesswork and intuition, I have decided that the following variables are most likely to affect a property's ultimate sale price:

Neighborhood, Condition1, Condition2, BldgType, OverallQual, OverallCond, ExterQual, ExterCond, CentralAir, Electrical, 1stFlrSF, 2ndFlrSF, KitchenAbvGr, KitchenQual, TotRmsAbvGrd, GarageArea, WoodDeckSF, OpenPorchSF, EnclosedPorch, and PoolArea

We will proceed with a simple analysis of our data to determine which of these variables correlate most highly with sale price.

In [3]:
num_vars = ['1stFlrSF',
            '2ndFlrSF',
            'GarageArea',
            'WoodDeckSF',
            'OpenPorchSF',
            'EnclosedPorch',
            'PoolArea']

for i in num_vars:
    x = df_train[i]
    y = df_train['SalePrice']
    
    plt.xlabel(i, fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('SalePrice', fontsize=12)

    plt.scatter(x, y)
    plt.show()

Of our numerical data, it seems that 1stFloorSF, 2ndFloorSF and GarageArea are most correlated with SalePrice. Now, it is entirely possible (and honestly likely) that one of the numerical variables that we eliminated in our heuristic once-over is better correlated with SalePrice than the ones we've shown here. However, I have chosen to forego that possibility and forge ahead with the (significantly) smaller subset of features. Should my future predictions prove horrendously poor, I shall certainly revisit this decision.

On to the categorical variables!

sns.set(style="ticks", color_codes=True)

We see that (bearing in mind the same caveats held for our numerical data), of our heuristically selected categorical variables, the ones most directly correlated with SalePrice appear to be OverallQual and TotRmsAbvGrd.

A More Legit Approach¶

Okay, maybe we should actually do this scientifically... (As you may have guessed, I'm following a tutorial, and at this point it was suggested that perhaps heuristics is not the most admirable approach to predictive data science. I suppose I'm inclined to agree.)

We shall start by generating a heatmap outlining the respective correlations between all of our features.

In [5]:
corrmat = df_train.corr()
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 9))
sns.heatmap(corrmat, vmax=.8, square=True)
Out[5]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7f4ce4f38d68>

Thankfully, we see that most of our heuristically selected features seem to be at least reasonably correlated with SalePrice. Yay for intuition! Of these (1stFloorSF, 2ndFloorSF, GarageArea, OverallQual and TotRmsAbvGrd), the latter three seem to show the strongest relationships, while 1stFloorSF and 2ndFloorSF are somewhat more tenuous. On the other side of the coin, our guesswork completely missed the relatively highly correlated GrLivArea, GarageCars and TotalBsmtSF. Can't win 'em all.

Let's not rely on our ability to identify colors in a heatmap to decide which variables are the most highly correlated. Seaborn allows us to select the n most correlated features and create a smaller heatmap. Let's ensure that our intuition is correct.

In [6]:
k = 10 
cols = corrmat.nlargest(k, 'SalePrice')['SalePrice'].index
cm = np.corrcoef(df_train[cols].values.T)
sns.set(font_scale=1.25)
hm = sns.heatmap(cm, cbar=True, annot=True, square=True, fmt='.2f', annot_kws={'size': 10}, yticklabels=cols.values, xticklabels=cols.values)
plt.show()

Let's do a quick sanity check to ensure that these variables make sense:

  • OverallQual: Yeah, no surprise here. It's kind of a weird metric, though. What considerations were taken to determine this value? Does it overlap with other variables?

  • GrLivArea: Makes sense.

  • GarageCars: Seems a little odd. I mean, maybe people care a lot about car-specific garage space.

  • GarageArea, TotalBsmtSF and 1stFlrSF: I get it. One question: are these values included in GrLivArea? What exactly is a "living area"?

  • FullBath, TotRmsAbvGrd and YearBuilt: Seems normal; I get it, but how many people are living in bunkers?; Yup, fine.

Let's keep OverallQual, GrLivArea, GarageCars and TotalBsmtSF. (I'll admit, these choices were more than a little influenced by the tutorial I'm following.) Oh, and let's look at how these variables all compare with each other.

In [7]:
sns.set()
cols = ['SalePrice', 'OverallQual', 'GrLivArea', 'GarageCars', 'TotalBsmtSF']
sns.pairplot(df_train[cols], height = 2.5)
plt.show()

That's pretty neat, eh? How about that one cheap house with the huge basement? Makes you wonder what they were doing down there...

Moving Right Along¶

Alright! We've done some preliminary feature analysis, both heuristically and somewhat less so. We feel (hopefully) familiar with the variables we've been provided, and have chosen a subset of them on which we will focus our predictions. Let's clean up that data and move on to the fun part. (Just kidding! All of this is a fucking blast ...Right?)

We'll begin by getting an assessment of how much data is missing for each feature. This is helpful because any feature that is missing a substantially large subset of datapoints is more likely to confuse our predictions than help.

In [8]:
total = df_train.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
percent = (df_train.isnull().sum() / df_train.isnull().count()).sort_values(ascending=False)
missing_data = pd.concat([total, percent], axis=1, keys=['Total', 'Percent'])
missing_data.head(20)

It seems that the first 19 features all have some missing data. That's too bad. Now, if any of these features were highly correlated with SalePrice (read: if we cared), we might consider going in and replacing these null values with the mean or expected value for that feature. However, as luck would have it, none of these features are ones we decided to care about in the previous section. Let's delete 'em! (Yeah, yeah, maybe this is heavy-handed. But it's also practice and I have little desire to make this problem more complicated that it needs to be. Fuck it. Never look back.)

In [9]:
df_train = df_train.drop((missing_data[missing_data['Total'] > 0]).index,1)
df_train.isnull().sum().max()
Out[9]:
0

Now that we've removed all the features with missing data, let's deal with those datapoints that seem to fall outside of the normal trend (that is to say, the outliers). Remember that cheap house with the big basement? That didn't seem normal. Let's find all the datapoints like that.

We'll begin by standardizing the SalePrice data. This means that we will scale the prices such that the mean price is 0 and standard deviation is 1. Fortunately, sklearn can do this automatically.

In [10]:

print(low_range)

print(high_range)

We can see that in the low end of prices, things seem to be relatively consistent. This makes sense. Houses can only be so cheap; there is probably a informal glassfloor for housing prices, independent of how garbage the house is. On the high end, however, there seem to be a few outliers. Again, this is to be expected. Someone is going to try (and probably succeed at) selling their house for well over the markt price. We'll keep an eye on those.

Let's take a moment to talk about that cheap house with the big basement. That sure seemed like an outlier. Let's take a closer look.
